# TypeScript Standards

## Typing (strict)
- `tsconfig` runs in `strict: true` mode; `tsc --noEmit` must pass with zero errors.
- NEVER use `any`. Use precise types, generics, or `unknown` + narrowing.
- No non-null assertions (`!`) to silence the checker — narrow properly.
- Model structured data as `interface`/`type` (or `zod` schemas for runtime validation),
  never loose untyped objects.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
function handle(msg: any) { return msg.jobId; }

// ✅ GOOD
interface MapTask { jobId: string; taskId: string; fileKeys: string[]; C: number; }
function handle(msg: MapTask): string { return msg.jobId; }
```

## Runtime validation at boundaries
Validate external input (HTTP bodies, queue messages) with `zod` and infer the TS type:

```typescript
import { z } from "zod";
export const mapTaskSchema = z.object({
  jobId: z.string(), taskId: z.string(), fileKeys: z.array(z.string()).max(5), C: z.number().int(),
});
export type MapTask = z.infer<typeof mapTaskSchema>;
```

## Tooling (must pass before commit / in CI)
- `tsc --noEmit` (types)
- `eslint .` (lint, `@typescript-eslint` with `no-explicit-any` as error)
- `prettier --check .` (formatting)
- `vitest` / `jest` (tests)
